WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.720
&gt;&gt; I'd like to welcome Chris McDougall to
Google today.

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:11.120
Chris is a former war correspondent for the
Associated Press, and now a contributing editor

00:00:11.120 --> 00:00:13.930
for Men's Health.
He's a three time National Magazine Award

00:00:13.930 --> 00:00:17.510
finalist.
He's written for Esquire, New York Times Magazine,

00:00:17.510 --> 00:00:21.750
Outside Men's Journal, and the New York Magazine.
And you may have seen him recently on the

00:00:21.750 --> 00:00:27.080
Daily Show, speaking about his book, "Born
to Run," which he's speaking about again today

00:00:27.080 --> 00:00:31.130
for us.
I hope some of you got copies.

00:00:31.130 --> 00:00:36.760
The book is a chronicle of the tribe of the
Tarahumara, who live in Chihuahua, Mexico,

00:00:36.760 --> 00:00:40.750
and their extraordinary running ability, as
well as the politics surrounding running in

00:00:40.750 --> 00:00:43.999
this particular tribe.
And I'm very excited to welcome Chris to speak

00:00:43.999 --> 00:00:44.999
with us today.
Come on up.

00:00:44.999 --> 00:00:45.999
&gt;&gt; [Clapping]

00:00:45.999 --> 00:00:54.329
Chris McDougall: Hi. Thanks a lot for having
me in today.

00:00:54.329 --> 00:00:57.039
You know, it's weird.
I've been spending five months now, talking

00:00:57.039 --> 00:00:59.139
about what should be the simplest thing on
Earth.

00:00:59.139 --> 00:01:02.789
You know, just moving one leg, moving the
other leg, and going that direction.

00:01:02.789 --> 00:01:07.970
And yet, it has been really remarkable how
complicated this topic is.

00:01:07.970 --> 00:01:13.210
I don't know if any of you saw that raging
debate yesterday online on the New York Times

00:01:13.210 --> 00:01:17.580
website.
There was a posting about whether running

00:01:17.580 --> 00:01:22.380
in bare feet is good for you.
And out of the shadows, all the barefoot runners

00:01:22.380 --> 00:01:26.890
came roaring out saying like, "Why the hell
are shoes the default position?" You know?

00:01:26.890 --> 00:01:30.539
"Why isn't the question, Are running in shoes
good for you?"

00:01:30.539 --> 00:01:34.520
You know, "Why is it this notion that shoes
are somehow better than bare feet?"

00:01:34.520 --> 00:01:41.719
So, I'll get into that whole controversy in
a little bit, because it's kind of intriguing.

00:01:41.719 --> 00:01:47.579
But, first, I'd like to tell you a little
bit about how this whole thing began.

00:01:47.579 --> 00:01:50.609
Well, let me read for you a little bit.
Have a lot of you already read the book?

00:01:50.609 --> 00:01:54.100
No? Good. Excellent.
I've gone to some places where I try and pull

00:01:54.100 --> 00:01:56.960
a little surprise out of the book, and people
are sort of nodding along.

00:01:56.960 --> 00:02:02.520
They've already been there, so. Okay.
[reading] It all began with a simple question

00:02:02.520 --> 00:02:06.080
that no one could answer.
It was a five-word puzzle that led me to a

00:02:06.080 --> 00:02:11.450
photo of a very fast man in a very short skirt.
And from there, it only got stranger.

00:02:11.450 --> 00:02:15.920
Soon, I was dealing with a murder, drug guerrillas,
and a one-armed man with a cream cheese cup

00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:20.060
strapped to his head.
I met a beautiful, blond forest ranger who

00:02:20.060 --> 00:02:25.470
slipped out of her clothes and found salvation
by running naked in the Idaho forests, and

00:02:25.470 --> 00:02:29.700
a young surfer babe in pigtails, who ran straight
toward her death in a desert.

00:02:29.700 --> 00:02:34.360
A talented young runner would die.
Two others would barely escape with their

00:02:34.360 --> 00:02:37.010
lives.
I kept looking, and I stumbled across the

00:02:37.010 --> 00:02:43.819
barefoot Batman, naked guy, the Kalahari bushmen,
the toenail amputee, a cult devoted to distance

00:02:43.819 --> 00:02:49.180
running and sex parts, the wild man of the
Blue Ridge Mountains, and ultimately, to the

00:02:49.180 --> 00:02:54.620
ancient tribe of the Tarahumara, and their
shadowy disciple Caballo Blanco.

00:02:54.620 --> 00:02:58.819
In the end, I got my answer, but only after
I found myself in the middle of the greatest

00:02:58.819 --> 00:03:04.120
race the world would never see -- the ultimate
fighting competition of foot races, an underground

00:03:04.120 --> 00:03:09.140
showdown, pitting some of the best ultra distance
runners of our time against the best ultra

00:03:09.140 --> 00:03:14.301
runners of all time, in the 50-mile race on
hidden trails only Tarahumara feet had ever

00:03:14.301 --> 00:03:18.799
touched.
[talking] And it all because, in January of

00:03:18.799 --> 00:03:22.849
2001, I asked my doctor this, "How come my
foot hurts?"

00:03:22.849 --> 00:03:27.840
That was the starting point. I was not a runner
at all.

00:03:27.840 --> 00:03:32.342
I was just a guy who was trying to work off,
you know, fat lunches every couple of days

00:03:32.342 --> 00:03:34.540
by running two or three miles and that was
it.

00:03:34.540 --> 00:03:37.469
But, after a few months, I was constantly
getting hurt.

00:03:37.469 --> 00:03:42.190
You know, I had Achilles' pain and arch pain
and heel pain and hamstring pulled and lower

00:03:42.190 --> 00:03:44.980
back pain.
And you know, I wasn't even attempting marathons.

00:03:44.980 --> 00:03:48.790
I was doing two or three miles every couple
days.

00:03:48.790 --> 00:03:53.180
The breaking point was, one day I went out
for a little 3-mile jog on a snow-covered

00:03:53.180 --> 00:04:00.040
road on a dirt, farm trail in the middle of
Amish farm country, technically the most forgiving

00:04:00.040 --> 00:04:04.730
surface you can run along on planet Earth.
After two miles, this blinding pain shot up

00:04:04.730 --> 00:04:06.530
my foot.
I went to see another sports medicine doctor,

00:04:06.530 --> 00:04:11.969
who said, "What do you expect, you know?
Running is bad for humans. The impact is bad

00:04:11.969 --> 00:04:14.420
for you. You keep this up"
-- particularly me, because at that point,

00:04:14.420 --> 00:04:20.140
I was like 240 pounds -- he says, "You keep
this up, and you have to get a new set of

00:04:20.140 --> 00:04:23.920
knees and a new set of hips."
So that was it. I gave up running and never

00:04:23.920 --> 00:04:31.660
planned to run again.
And the reason why is because of this pervasive

00:04:31.660 --> 00:04:35.530
attitude that exists in the world -- and so
pervasive that it's the kind of thing you

00:04:35.530 --> 00:04:40.630
hear all the time from the most respected
voices in the running world.

00:04:40.630 --> 00:04:46.030
I mean, let me just read you a quote.
This was a couple weeks ago from, you know,

00:04:46.030 --> 00:04:49.880
the editor of Runners World Magazine -- the
guy who you assume not only knows about running,

00:04:49.880 --> 00:04:52.550
but would want to sort of promote it and make
more people do it.

00:04:52.550 --> 00:04:58.080
And this is what he said on NPR -- he said,
"The concern I have is, a lot of people hear

00:04:58.080 --> 00:05:02.670
about these new shoes and read about and maybe
hear about this book called, 'Born to Run,'

00:05:02.670 --> 00:05:07.220
and feel like, 'Oh, I could just throw away
my running shoes and I'll just start tomorrow,

00:05:07.220 --> 00:05:11.630
and I'll become a barefoot runner.' If a lot
of runners, or all the runners out there in

00:05:11.630 --> 00:05:17.310
America, did that tomorrow, the vast majority
of them would get hurt very quickly and have

00:05:17.310 --> 00:05:20.810
to stop running for a very long time."
And the reason why you would get hurt very

00:05:20.810 --> 00:05:25.320
quickly and have to stop running for a long
time he said was because "the vast majority

00:05:25.320 --> 00:05:30.700
of people are not blessed in that way.
They've got some biomechanical inefficiencies."

00:05:30.700 --> 00:05:36.470
Okay, biomechanical inefficiencies.
Now, a guy named Dr. Maharam -- who is the

00:05:36.470 --> 00:05:42.360
medical consultant for the New York City Marathon,
and who's billed as the premier running position

00:05:42.360 --> 00:05:46.410
in the country -- says the same thing.
He said, if everyone tried to run in their

00:05:46.410 --> 00:05:50.080
bare feet, 95 percent of them would end up
in his office with injuries, because they

00:05:50.080 --> 00:05:54.740
are not 'biomechanically perfect'.
Now, you hear this, and you think, "Okay,

00:05:54.740 --> 00:06:00.030
well. If I were to prevent any organism from
performing any function, I will threaten it

00:06:00.030 --> 00:06:04.430
with pain. You know. Pain is a great dissuader."
So what they're telling you is, unless you

00:06:04.430 --> 00:06:08.310
are 'biomechanically perfect', running is
fraught with danger.

00:06:08.310 --> 00:06:10.840
It's this risky thing like trying to remove
your own appendix.

00:06:10.840 --> 00:06:15.130
"Don't try it at home."
And if you do, you better have the best possible

00:06:15.130 --> 00:06:18.431
equipment.
Now, that phrase, I've now heard over and

00:06:18.431 --> 00:06:20.800
over again for years.
And I was hearing it back when I was going

00:06:20.800 --> 00:06:23.410
to see sports medicine doctor.
They would look at me and say, "Well, you're

00:06:23.410 --> 00:06:29.000
not biomechanically perfect.
You need orthotics, you need cortisone shots.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:31.400
You need some $150 shoes, which you have to
throw away in three months.

00:06:31.400 --> 00:06:35.400
You get new $150 shoes."
But then, you know, you start to think about

00:06:35.400 --> 00:06:39.130
this, "Well, wait a minute.
What does 'biomechanically efficient' mean?"

00:06:39.130 --> 00:06:43.670
You hear that word and you think it means
'biologically efficient,' or 'biologically

00:06:43.670 --> 00:06:46.570
perfect.'
Well, biomechanical is not biological.

00:06:46.570 --> 00:06:49.970
Biomechanical just means you do it right,
period. You know?

00:06:49.970 --> 00:06:53.700
If you drop a kid in a pool and that kid starts
to sink, you don't say, "I'm sorry.

00:06:53.700 --> 00:06:56.270
You're not biomechanically efficient.
You're fucked, you know?" [laughter]

00:06:56.270 --> 00:07:01.280
No. You pull the kid out.
You give a few compressions, you know?

00:07:01.280 --> 00:07:04.360
And you teach him how to swim.
That's what's been lacking from this whole

00:07:04.360 --> 00:07:08.360
question about running.
Nobody ever tells you how to do this damn

00:07:08.360 --> 00:07:10.970
thing.
What they tell you to do is buy something.

00:07:10.970 --> 00:07:16.190
And we got into the situation today where,
you know, you're told over and over again,

00:07:16.190 --> 00:07:19.930
"Just buy something." as opposed to "Just
learn something."

00:07:19.930 --> 00:07:22.130
And that was the situation I found myself
in.

00:07:22.130 --> 00:07:26.610
I was constantly hurt.
You know, and I didn't particularly care about

00:07:26.610 --> 00:07:29.040
running.
But I had this feeling.

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:31.850
It was kind of instinct inside.
I just wanted to have that liberty, that freedom

00:07:31.850 --> 00:07:34.100
to run, that everybody else seemed to have.
That I remember having as a kid too.

00:07:34.100 --> 00:07:41.060
You never see a five-year-old doing hot yoga
or putting on shoes, or doing a stretch or

00:07:41.060 --> 00:07:44.760
any kind of warm up.
A five-year-old wants to go, a five-year-old

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:50.690
is gone -- at a sprint, all the time.
You never met a five-year-old on earth who

00:07:50.690 --> 00:07:55.880
says they hate running or they're tapering
or they're in training, you know? [laughter]

00:07:55.880 --> 00:07:58.910
Five-year-olds are just ready to fly all the
time.

00:07:58.910 --> 00:08:04.280
It's somewhere in that transit, there's sort
of an arc, where "Love running, Love running,

00:08:04.280 --> 00:08:07.090
Love running -- Hate running, Hate running,
Hate running" for the rest of your life.

00:08:07.090 --> 00:08:12.580
And that's where I became intrigued by is,
Where is that little tipping-over point between

00:08:12.580 --> 00:08:18.190
enjoying it naturally to taking it on as a
task to somehow giving up on it?

00:08:18.190 --> 00:08:23.270
And I found my answer, initially, when I was
down in Mexico researching a story for the

00:08:23.270 --> 00:08:29.150
New York Times magazine.
And I think sort of testament to the impact

00:08:29.150 --> 00:08:34.470
of the photo I was about to see that the second
I saw that photo, I immediately forgot about

00:08:34.470 --> 00:08:39.079
the assignment I was on.
And that assignment was to find this like,

00:08:39.079 --> 00:08:43.209
gorgeous, voluptuous, Mexican pop star, who
was secretly running her own fugitive brainwashing

00:08:43.209 --> 00:08:46.440
sex cult.
That's what I was looking for, but yet, I

00:08:46.440 --> 00:08:51.639
see this picture of this old man in a bathrobe
and sandals, running down this trail in these

00:08:51.639 --> 00:08:55.220
thin, little sandals.
And according to the caption, this guy had

00:08:55.220 --> 00:09:01.250
just run a hundred miles through the Rocky
Mountains and beaten hundreds of top, elite

00:09:01.250 --> 00:09:05.060
American ultra runners.
Fifty-five years old, running a hundred miles,

00:09:05.060 --> 00:09:10.410
in sandals, beating the best in the world.
And I look at this picture thinking, "Now,

00:09:10.410 --> 00:09:14.259
what's that dude doing that I'm not doing?
How come I'm told that 26-miles is the ultimate

00:09:14.259 --> 00:09:19.050
challenge, you know, 'You go beyond 26, you
could die like Pheidippides."

00:09:19.050 --> 00:09:22.649
This guy just did a hundred miles in sandals,
and he's 55 years old.

00:09:22.649 --> 00:09:27.350
He was twice my age, running four times the
distance in the thinnest shoes imaginable.

00:09:27.350 --> 00:09:36.389
That was my first introduction to the Tarahumara.
I made a lot of mistakes along the way trying

00:09:36.389 --> 00:09:41.470
to understand what they're all about.
And I wish I had originally spoken to a guy

00:09:41.470 --> 00:09:50.279
named doctor Joe Vigil, who is a distant running
coach in Colorado, who -- he's a strange guy,

00:09:50.279 --> 00:09:54.829
because even late in his life, as the most
successful running coach of all time, I think

00:09:54.829 --> 00:09:59.459
he's plagued by this roaring sense of vulnerability
 -- that somebody's always going to pull something

00:09:59.459 --> 00:10:05.019
out that he can never be prepared for.
So Vigil does stuff like turn up at the Leadville

00:10:05.019 --> 00:10:08.821
Trail 100, which is a freaky mountain race,
in the middle of nowhere in the middle of

00:10:08.821 --> 00:10:11.180
the night.
And there he is, 70 years old, like huddle

00:10:11.180 --> 00:10:15.329
in the woods with a little cup of coffee waiting
to watch these guys run by.

00:10:15.329 --> 00:10:20.610
He was there in 1994, because, long before
I'd heard of the Tarahumara Indians, he'd

00:10:20.610 --> 00:10:25.870
heard about them.
And nobody else on the planet could care less

00:10:25.870 --> 00:10:31.040
about freaky guys in bathrobes and sandals,
or even less about freakier guys who remove

00:10:31.040 --> 00:10:33.160
their own toenails and run these 100-mile
races.

00:10:33.160 --> 00:10:37.350
They remove their toenails, because they -- I
don't know if you saw the Time story yesterday

00:10:37.350 --> 00:10:41.420
about ultra runners keep jamming their toes
against the front of their shoes, so they

00:10:41.420 --> 00:10:45.290
will have their toenails surgically removed
and then burnt off with acid.

00:10:45.290 --> 00:10:48.990
So yeah, just remove some deadweight and move
on.

00:10:48.990 --> 00:10:53.580
So there was Vigil.
Vigil turned out in 1994, because it was one

00:10:53.580 --> 00:10:57.600
of the few times that the Tarahumara Indians
had ever left their homes in the bottom of

00:10:57.600 --> 00:11:00.600
the Copper Canyons of Mexico to come out and
compete.

00:11:00.600 --> 00:11:08.740
And this is what he saw.
And this is what intrigued him so much. [pause]

00:11:08.740 --> 00:11:18.399
[reading] Over the previous years, Coach Vigil
had become convinced that the next leap forward

00:11:18.399 --> 00:11:24.560
in human endurance would come from a dimension
he dreaded getting into -- character.

00:11:24.560 --> 00:11:27.700
Not the character that other coaches were
always rah, rah, rah-ing about.

00:11:27.700 --> 00:11:33.519
Vigil wasn't talking about grit or hunger
or the "size of the fight in the dog".

00:11:33.519 --> 00:11:39.430
In fact, he meant the exact opposite.
Vigil's notion of character wasn't toughness.

00:11:39.430 --> 00:11:45.240
It was compassion, kindness, love. That's
right, 'love'.

00:11:45.240 --> 00:11:49.980
Now, Vigil had figured out the body.
So now, he was moving on to the brain.

00:11:49.980 --> 00:11:54.430
Specifically, he wanted to know, How do you
make anybody actually want to do any of this

00:11:54.430 --> 00:11:57.449
stuff?
How do you make someone actually want to run?

00:11:57.449 --> 00:12:02.370
And that was the real secret of the Tarahumara.
They've never forgotten what it felt like

00:12:02.370 --> 00:12:06.779
to love running.
They remember that running was mankind's first

00:12:06.779 --> 00:12:12.509
fine art -- our original act of inspired creation.
Way before we were scratching pictures on

00:12:12.509 --> 00:12:16.889
caves or beating rhythms on hollowed trees,
we were perfecting the art of combining our

00:12:16.889 --> 00:12:22.410
breath and mind and muscles into fluid self-propulsion
over wild terrain.

00:12:22.410 --> 00:12:26.660
And when our ancestors finally did make their
first cave paintings, what were the first

00:12:26.660 --> 00:12:29.910
designs?
A downward slash, lightning bolts through

00:12:29.910 --> 00:12:34.019
the bottom and the middle -- Behold, the running
man.

00:12:34.019 --> 00:12:37.350
Distance running was revered, because it was
indispensable.

00:12:37.350 --> 00:12:41.170
It was the way we survived and thrived and
spread across the planet.

00:12:41.170 --> 00:12:46.230
You ran to eat and to avoid being eaten.
You ran to find a mate and to impress her,

00:12:46.230 --> 00:12:49.389
and with her, you ran off to start a new life
together.

00:12:49.389 --> 00:12:52.999
You had to love running or you wouldn't live
to love anything else.

00:12:52.999 --> 00:12:57.930
And like everything else we love -- everything
we sentimentally call our 'passions' and 'desires'

00:12:57.930 --> 00:13:04.110
 -- it's really an encoded ancestral necessity.
We were born to run.

00:13:04.110 --> 00:13:08.329
We were born because we run.
We're all running people, as the Tarahumara

00:13:08.329 --> 00:13:16.270
have never forgotten. [pause]
[reading] So there he was, Joe Vigil, an old

00:13:16.270 --> 00:13:19.980
man alone in the woods, and he suddenly felt
a burst of immortality.

00:13:19.980 --> 00:13:24.730
He was on to something, something huge.
It wasn't just how to run; it was how to live.

00:13:24.730 --> 00:13:27.779
The essence of who we are as a species and
what we're meant to be.

00:13:27.779 --> 00:13:33.240
Vigil had read Carl Lumholtz, the ancient
Norwegian explorer.

00:13:33.240 --> 00:13:37.350
And, at that moment, Lumholtz's words revealed
their hidden treasure.

00:13:37.350 --> 00:13:43.300
So that's what he meant when he called the
Tarahumara "The founders and makers of the

00:13:43.300 --> 00:13:46.999
history of mankind."
Perhaps all of our troubles -- all the violence

00:13:46.999 --> 00:13:51.619
and obesity and illness, all the depression
and greed we can't overcome -- began when

00:13:51.619 --> 00:13:55.709
we stopped living as a running people.
If you deny your nature, it will erupt in

00:13:55.709 --> 00:14:04.399
some other, uglier way.
[talking] What Vigil was on to was this really

00:14:04.399 --> 00:14:09.930
strange correlation between sports and social
living.

00:14:09.930 --> 00:14:16.430
The Tarahumara are remarkable for three things.
Number one, when the Conquistadors arrived

00:14:16.430 --> 00:14:20.850
in Mexico, back in the 1600s, you basically
had two choices: You either fight back or

00:14:20.850 --> 00:14:24.779
haul ass.
The Mayans and the Aztecs fought back, which

00:14:24.779 --> 00:14:27.630
is why you see very few Mayans and Aztecs
anymore.

00:14:27.630 --> 00:14:29.829
The Tarahumara just turned around and took
off.

00:14:29.829 --> 00:14:35.839
They disappeared down into this vast, spider-webbing
network of canyons -- one of the most inaccessible

00:14:35.839 --> 00:14:39.430
places on the planet.
And they've essentially been there ever since

00:14:39.430 --> 00:14:43.740
 -- unchanged -- living the same way they
have for tens of thousands of years.

00:14:43.740 --> 00:14:49.459
So essentially, you can look at them as this
born-again Smithsonian exhibit.

00:14:49.459 --> 00:14:53.690
Nothing has changed since the Stone Age for
the Tarahumara.

00:14:53.690 --> 00:14:56.889
That's thing number one.
Number two, their running ability has been

00:14:56.889 --> 00:15:01.769
fabled throughout history.
Periodically, people would come across the

00:15:01.769 --> 00:15:07.110
Tarahumara hundreds of miles from the canyons.
These guys would tear off on 300 and 400-mile

00:15:07.110 --> 00:15:11.819
runs -- not just for a purpose, you know,
like the Navahos used to have a whole system

00:15:11.819 --> 00:15:14.959
of messengers.
The Tarahumara essentially did it for fun.

00:15:14.959 --> 00:15:19.119
Their recreational games were these super-long,
endurance contests.

00:15:19.119 --> 00:15:22.300
You know, we won a marathon?
They'll run ten marathons back to back to

00:15:22.300 --> 00:15:25.059
back, for fun, as a game.
That's number two.

00:15:25.059 --> 00:15:29.990
Number three -- and this is where Vigil was
really intrigued.

00:15:29.990 --> 00:15:38.410
The Tarahumara are free from crime, violence,
warfare, heart disease, high cholesterol,

00:15:38.410 --> 00:15:44.110
diabetes, clinical depression, high blood
pressure, domestic abuse.

00:15:44.110 --> 00:15:49.380
Everything that we in the western world are
spending billions trying to eradicate -- things

00:15:49.380 --> 00:15:54.780
people are winning Nobel prizes for -- these
dudes sussed out thousands of years ago, and

00:15:54.780 --> 00:16:00.200
have never had a problem ever since.
So you can see this as some kind of quirky,

00:16:00.200 --> 00:16:03.329
indigenous, kind of eugenic society where
everything is beautiful.

00:16:03.329 --> 00:16:08.040
Or, you can be like Vigil and say, "These
things aren't coincidences."

00:16:08.040 --> 00:16:10.949
If you have two outliers in one community,
there's a cause and effect there; it's not

00:16:10.949 --> 00:16:14.569
a coincidence.
The people who run the most, and people who

00:16:14.569 --> 00:16:19.009
are the healthiest -- not just physically,
but psychologically and socially -- have got

00:16:19.009 --> 00:16:23.779
some kind of ancient wisdom going on.
That's what he wanted to find out.

00:16:23.779 --> 00:16:27.459
Unfortunately, he was 70 years old and on
the verge of having triple bypass.

00:16:27.459 --> 00:16:32.720
So that was it for Vigil's possibility of
going down into the canyons.

00:16:32.720 --> 00:16:35.579
Luckily, I was much younger and dumber than
he was at the time.

00:16:35.579 --> 00:16:40.819
So I thought I could just fly on down there,
get some quotes, get the hell out, have my

00:16:40.819 --> 00:16:44.559
article, and be done with it.
What I didn't realize is, these Copper Canyons

00:16:44.559 --> 00:16:49.139
 -- you know, it's -- the way you remain a
reclusive tribe is by, number one, being a

00:16:49.139 --> 00:16:53.790
place that's really hard to get to, and number
two, not answering any questions when strangers

00:16:53.790 --> 00:16:57.420
show up.
I found myself down at the bottom of the canyons,

00:16:57.420 --> 00:17:05.610
and I actually had the luck to locate a hidden
home of a guy named Arnulfo Quimare, one of

00:17:05.610 --> 00:17:10.250
the greatest, living, Tarahumara runners.
His home is so concealed that, if you were

00:17:10.250 --> 00:17:12.380
standing on it right now, you would not realize
it's there.

00:17:12.380 --> 00:17:18.180
It is totally blended into the landscape.
I actually got there, found this hidden home.

00:17:18.180 --> 00:17:20.730
Arnulfo happened to be there -- wasn't off
on a 400-mile run.

00:17:20.730 --> 00:17:24.000
He happened to be right there.
It was two o'clock in the afternoon.

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:28.630
We sat down. I looked him in the eye.
I started to ask my question, and for the

00:17:28.630 --> 00:17:33.430
next four hours, he said absolutely nothing
 -- just stared at me, and then his eyes would

00:17:33.430 --> 00:17:38.980
just sort of drift off like, you know, maybe
heard something, but kind of wished he hadn't.

00:17:38.980 --> 00:17:41.780
And this went on and on and on for hours.
He just wouldn't talk.

00:17:41.780 --> 00:17:45.950
And finally, the guy who was guiding said,
"Let's get out of here."

00:17:45.950 --> 00:17:50.030
So, we got up, and we sort of retreated.
And there's nowhere else to go.

00:17:50.030 --> 00:17:54.220
So we went deeper into the canyons, and we
found this little Tarahumara schoolhouse.

00:17:54.220 --> 00:17:59.010
And there's a schoolteacher there, who's half-Mexican,
half-Tarahumara -- one of the few guys from

00:17:59.010 --> 00:18:01.530
the tribe who'd ever actually left and gone
to the outside world.

00:18:01.530 --> 00:18:05.690
And he gave us a place to stay for the night
and a little bowl of beans.

00:18:05.690 --> 00:18:10.360
And he tried to console me by saying, "Well,
what do you expect, you know?

00:18:10.360 --> 00:18:14.950
They're not going to talk to you.
These guys -- they are so private that you'd

00:18:14.950 --> 00:18:19.510
have to be down here for years.
You'd have to be down here about as long as

00:18:19.510 --> 00:18:22.780
the White Horse before they're going to talk."
I'm sort of eating my beans going, "Okay,

00:18:22.780 --> 00:18:25.640
yeah. I see your point. Wait -- what White
Horse?"

00:18:25.640 --> 00:18:30.890
And he tells me this story about some mysterious
guy who had appeared down the canyons 15 years

00:18:30.890 --> 00:18:37.360
ago -- just came running on into the settlement,
essentially naked, pair of sandals, pair of

00:18:37.360 --> 00:18:41.850
shorts, and got a cup of water and a little
bit of food, and then disappeared again, off

00:18:41.850 --> 00:18:44.890
into the canyons.
And he would periodically reappear.

00:18:44.890 --> 00:18:47.800
And over the months and the years, he'd become
friendly with the Tarahumara.

00:18:47.800 --> 00:18:52.430
And bit by bit, they had sort of absorbed
him into the tribe, and looked at him as kind

00:18:52.430 --> 00:19:00.530
of like this sort of freaky, you know, foreign,
ghostly half-cousin.

00:19:00.530 --> 00:19:05.380
All they knew about this guy was, he wasn't
from down there, and he had been there for

00:19:05.380 --> 00:19:09.610
long enough where he actually had absorbed
the same secrets of the Tarahumara I was trying

00:19:09.610 --> 00:19:12.320
to figure out.
So they said, "You go find the White Horse,

00:19:12.320 --> 00:19:16.781
and you'll find your answers."
Sounded really good at the time, you know,

00:19:16.781 --> 00:19:20.290
until you step back and you look up at these
vast canyons and realize there's one dude

00:19:20.290 --> 00:19:23.630
out there somewhere and even they didn't know
where he was, and they'd known him for 15

00:19:23.630 --> 00:19:28.200
years.
Defying all odds -- and I sort of get into

00:19:28.200 --> 00:19:32.340
this in detail in the book how it actually
turned out, but I actually located this guy.

00:19:32.340 --> 00:19:35.660
And he is just as reclusive as the Tarahumara,
except for one thing.

00:19:35.660 --> 00:19:41.230
At that point, he realized that the thing
he was there to discover, was on the verge

00:19:41.230 --> 00:19:43.890
of being extinguished.
You know, the Tarahumara only number about

00:19:43.890 --> 00:19:49.310
40,000 today.
Of that 40,000, only a small minority still

00:19:49.310 --> 00:19:53.820
practice the ancient running traditions.
And what this guy -- the White Horse, Caballo

00:19:53.820 --> 00:19:58.230
Blanco -- realized was that, in his lifetime,
that candle could be extinguished.

00:19:58.230 --> 00:20:04.590
That secret -- that synergy between the way
the body operates and the way society operates

00:20:04.590 --> 00:20:09.060
that Vigil wanted to find out could be gone
in our lifetime.

00:20:09.060 --> 00:20:14.920
So this guy, the White Horse, had this plan.
What he wanted to do was find people like

00:20:14.920 --> 00:20:17.740
him.
Now, think about that right there too.

00:20:17.740 --> 00:20:21.440
You know, a guy who lives by himself in the
bottom of the canyon wants to find other people

00:20:21.440 --> 00:20:26.910
like him out there in the world, bring them
down to the canyons, and set up a 50-mile

00:20:26.910 --> 00:20:33.230
race between this sort of elite group of specially
sort of karmically-screened, American runners

00:20:33.230 --> 00:20:37.360
and the Tarahumara.
Again, seems like a good idea until you realize,

00:20:37.360 --> 00:20:40.820
"I just met one of these guys.
This dude wouldn't even talk to me, let alone

00:20:40.820 --> 00:20:45.060
hike 30-miles through the canyons for a 50-mile
race."

00:20:45.060 --> 00:20:50.900
But that was his plan.
And I really wanted to be a part of it, despite

00:20:50.900 --> 00:20:54.360
the obstacles that -- There's no way in hell
you can have this race; No way racers were

00:20:54.360 --> 00:20:57.510
going to show up; and There's no way I could
do it.

00:20:57.510 --> 00:21:03.960
I couldn't run a mile, let alone 50-miles.
But I became really intrigued by something

00:21:03.960 --> 00:21:09.630
I learned from the White Horse.
In the time I'd met him, he was in his 50's.

00:21:09.630 --> 00:21:16.290
But the time he came down to the canyons,
he was almost a bizarrely like _____ for me.

00:21:16.290 --> 00:21:20.650
He was the same age I was at that moment.
He was the same height. He was the same shoe

00:21:20.650 --> 00:21:23.170
size.
And he had the same running injuries.

00:21:23.170 --> 00:21:26.090
And what he was telling me was, when he went
down to the canyons, he was in his like, late

00:21:26.090 --> 00:21:31.900
30's, early 40's -- and had busted up ankles
and feet, had always wanted to run, but had

00:21:31.900 --> 00:21:35.190
given it up.
And then, within a few months, he was running

00:21:35.190 --> 00:21:38.260
like wild fire.
And he actually took me out for a little jog,

00:21:38.260 --> 00:21:42.320
just to show me what he meant.
And the kind of running he did was unlike

00:21:42.320 --> 00:21:45.210
any kind of running I'd ever seen in my life.
I don't know if you've ever been out here

00:21:45.210 --> 00:21:49.650
for like, the New York City Marathon, and
you watch 50,000 people go by, and it's like

00:21:49.650 --> 00:21:52.700
50,000 different running styles, you know?
Everyone's sort of grimacing, pushing along.

00:21:52.700 --> 00:21:56.440
And the only thing they have in common is,
they're all miserable.

00:21:56.440 --> 00:22:01.840
[laughter] But I watched this dude, Caballo,
and this guy is in his 50's.

00:22:01.840 --> 00:22:05.850
And we went up this steep trail.
And he went up -- it looked like he was running

00:22:05.850 --> 00:22:09.010
downhill instead of uphill.
It was like smoke going up into the air, just

00:22:09.010 --> 00:22:12.410
[chuu chuu chuu chuu] this slid on up the
hill.

00:22:12.410 --> 00:22:15.490
And it looked exactly like some of the Tarahumara
children I'd seen the day before.

00:22:15.490 --> 00:22:24.340
Here's a guy in his 50's, running like five-year-olds,
not just with the same joyfulness and elasticity,

00:22:24.340 --> 00:22:28.440
but with the same exact style.
And, again, I'm just used to being told, "You

00:22:28.440 --> 00:22:30.690
run the way you run."
You know, there's no right or wrong way.

00:22:30.690 --> 00:22:34.540
You just run the way you run.
Some of you pronate, some of you supinate,

00:22:34.540 --> 00:22:37.000
heel to toe.
Doesn't matter what the hell you do.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:38.180
You just run the way you run, and you buy
the right shoe.

00:22:38.180 --> 00:22:41.690
I'm watching this dude, who basically is not
even in shoes.

00:22:41.690 --> 00:22:47.450
He's in this crappy, old pair of sandals.
And somehow, coincidentally or not, his running

00:22:47.450 --> 00:22:52.140
biomechanics -- the way he is running -- looks
identical to a five-year-old I'd seen the

00:22:52.140 --> 00:22:55.220
day before.
And I sort of think, "There's something here,

00:22:55.220 --> 00:22:57.570
you know?
Maybe there actually is a right way to do

00:22:57.570 --> 00:23:00.790
this thing.
And maybe that's the first step toward unlocking

00:23:00.790 --> 00:23:02.980
the secret of the Tarahumara."
It's the simplest thing of all.

00:23:02.980 --> 00:23:06.930
You learn how to do it right, and everything
else falls in place.

00:23:06.930 --> 00:23:10.500
So that became my ambition.
I wanted to come back to the States, spend

00:23:10.500 --> 00:23:16.430
nine months training for this race to see
if I could learn how to run like a Tarahumara,

00:23:16.430 --> 00:23:22.420
and turn myself into kind of like a 21st century
Caballo Blanco, and go back for that race.

00:23:22.420 --> 00:23:25.870
And see if, just by learning the motion -- you
know, there's the theory of psychology that

00:23:25.870 --> 00:23:29.731
if you want to be happy, the first step is
just to 'act happy', you know?

00:23:29.731 --> 00:23:35.230
Just smile a lot, and then you actually become
happy by mimicking the behavior of someone

00:23:35.230 --> 00:23:37.290
who is happy.
That's what I wanted to do.

00:23:37.290 --> 00:23:40.850
If I could mimic the behavior of the Tarahumara,
maybe I could get the rest of the benefits.

00:23:40.850 --> 00:23:43.690
So things are kind of cool, except for one
thing.

00:23:43.690 --> 00:23:48.340
Nine months later, I actually -- through this
whole process I described -- had actually

00:23:48.340 --> 00:23:52.590
learned how to run like a Tarahumara.
I was ready to go back down to the canyons,

00:23:52.590 --> 00:23:56.490
but I was still missing two things.
Number one was, no other racers.

00:23:56.490 --> 00:24:00.660
It was just basically me, this old dude, and
maybe or maybe not a bunch of Indians -- still

00:24:00.660 --> 00:24:02.310
to be determined.
There were no racers.

00:24:02.310 --> 00:24:07.510
And secondly, you know, I still had not gotten
the spirit of the thing. You know?

00:24:07.510 --> 00:24:12.120
I'd done the motions and the behavior, but
I still didn't quite get what the cause and

00:24:12.120 --> 00:24:15.260
effect was.
And then, I made this phone call to this girl

00:24:15.260 --> 00:24:18.670
named Jenn Shelton.
I was researching an article about ultra runners

00:24:18.670 --> 00:24:24.550
for Runners World Magazine.
And I called up Jenn Shelton, because she

00:24:24.550 --> 00:24:30.990
is one of the few runners who is in her 20's,
and is still doing these long races.

00:24:30.990 --> 00:24:34.390
I may have lost my page here so I may not
be able to do it. [pause]

00:24:34.390 --> 00:24:46.370
What was intriguing to me about Jenn was that
her first race that she ever ran in her life

00:24:46.370 --> 00:24:52.070
wasn't a 5K -- wasn't a 10K, wasn't a marathon
 -- it was a 50-mile race, a trail race.

00:24:52.070 --> 00:24:56.920
She went out there in a pair of surf baggies
and a cotton sweatshirt and broke the course

00:24:56.920 --> 00:24:59.330
record.
She was 19 years old at the time.

00:24:59.330 --> 00:25:04.600
So I call her up on the phone to find out
why she was wasting her time as a teenager

00:25:04.600 --> 00:25:09.050
running these races on Saturday nights.
So I said to her, "So why not marathons? Don't

00:25:09.050 --> 00:25:14.870
you think you could qualify for the Olympics?"
She goes, "Dude, seriously. The qualifying

00:25:14.870 --> 00:25:21.350
standard is 248. Anybody can do that."
Jenn could run a sub-three-hour marathon while

00:25:21.350 --> 00:25:27.000
wearing a string bikini and chugging a beer
at mile 23, and she would, just five days

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:30.330
after running a 50-mile trail race in the
Blue Ridge Mountains.

00:25:30.330 --> 00:25:34.001
Yeah, but then what?
I hate all this hype about the marathon. Where's

00:25:34.001 --> 00:25:37.720
the mystery?
I know this girl who's training for the trials,

00:25:37.720 --> 00:25:40.833
and she's got every single workout planned
for like, the next three years.

00:25:40.833 --> 00:25:44.270
She's doing speed work on the track like every
day.

00:25:44.270 --> 00:25:46.990
I couldn't take it man.
I was supposed to run with her once at six

00:25:46.990 --> 00:25:51.480
in the morning, and I called her up at two
a.m. to tell her I was shit-faced on margaritas

00:25:51.480 --> 00:25:57.020
and probably not going to make it.
Jenn didn't have a coach or training program.

00:25:57.020 --> 00:26:00.410
She didn't even own a watch.
She just rolled out of bed every morning,

00:26:00.410 --> 00:26:05.020
downed the veggie burger, and ran as far and
as fast as she felt like -- which usually

00:26:05.020 --> 00:26:09.680
turned out to be about 20-miles.
So she says to me, "You know, I never really

00:26:09.680 --> 00:26:13.740
discussed this with anyone, because it sounds
pretty pretentious, but I started running

00:26:13.740 --> 00:26:18.600
ultras to become a better person."
I thought, "Man, if you could run a hundred

00:26:18.600 --> 00:26:23.660
miles, you'd be in this zen state.
You'd be the fucking Buddha bringing peace

00:26:23.660 --> 00:26:27.350
and a smile to the world."
In my case, it didn't work.

00:26:27.350 --> 00:26:31.240
I'm the same old punk-ass as ever, but there's
always a hope that it would turn you into

00:26:31.240 --> 00:26:35.370
the person you want to be -- a better, more
peaceful person.

00:26:35.370 --> 00:26:38.610
She kept going on.
"You know, when I'm out on a long run, the

00:26:38.610 --> 00:26:42.340
only thing at life that matters is finishing
the run.

00:26:42.340 --> 00:26:45.590
For once my brain isn't going blah, blah,
blah.

00:26:45.590 --> 00:26:49.150
Everything quiets down.
And the only thing going on is pure flow.

00:26:49.150 --> 00:26:52.530
It's just me and the movement and the motion.
That's what I love.

00:26:52.530 --> 00:26:56.360
Just being a barbarian, running through the
woods.

00:26:56.360 --> 00:26:59.410
You know, listening to Jenn was like communing
with the ghost of Caballo Blanco.

00:26:59.410 --> 00:27:04.490
So, I said to her, "You know, it's weird how
much you sound like this guy I met in Mexico.

00:27:04.490 --> 00:27:08.610
I'm heading down there in a few weeks for
this race he's putting on with the Tarahumara."

00:27:08.610 --> 00:27:11.630
"No way!"
"And I think Scott Jurek" -- you know, the

00:27:11.630 --> 00:27:15.150
greatest ultra-distance runner in the world,
I think there's a chance he may be there too."

00:27:15.150 --> 00:27:20.240
"You're shitting me!" the budding Buddha exclaimed.
"Really? Can me and my friend go? Oh shit,

00:27:20.240 --> 00:27:26.270
we got midterms. Hang on. I'm going to have
to pull a fast one on them. Give me till tomorrow."

00:27:26.270 --> 00:27:28.580
And the next morning, as promised, I got this
message from Jenn.

00:27:28.580 --> 00:27:33.570
"My mom thinks you're a serial killer who's
going to murder us in the desert."

00:27:33.570 --> 00:27:34.570
&gt;&gt; [Laughter]

00:27:34.570 --> 00:27:38.690
Chris McDougall: "It's totally worth the risk.
So where do we meet you guys?"

00:27:38.690 --> 00:27:45.160
So that was it. That became the genesis.
A couple days later, against all odds, I suddenly

00:27:45.160 --> 00:27:52.600
found myself in El Paso, Texas, with Jenn,
who gave herself a black eye; Billy Bonehead

00:27:52.600 --> 00:27:57.710
Barnett, who passed out in my bathtub; a guy
named Barefoot Ted, who trained by running

00:27:57.710 --> 00:28:02.100
barefoot in the streets of Burbank pulling
his wife and daughter in a rickshaw; guy named

00:28:02.100 --> 00:28:06.731
Scott Jurek, who actually is a legitimate
runner, a 7-time winner of the Western States

00:28:06.731 --> 00:28:12.370
100, course record holder for the Badwater
ultra marathon Death Valley, and myself.

00:28:12.370 --> 00:28:19.460
And we ended up heading down for this race
with the Tarahumara and Caballo Blanco.

00:28:19.460 --> 00:28:23.590
Every step of the way I assumed was going
to be the last step, especially when -- on

00:28:23.590 --> 00:28:29.450
his first day as a guide -- Caballo lost two
out of the six people that were part of his

00:28:29.450 --> 00:28:31.920
group.
But eventually, he actually pulled off this

00:28:31.920 --> 00:28:34.920
race.
And it was beyond anything I could have expected.

00:28:34.920 --> 00:28:40.861
Rather than it being one of these head-to-head,
drudge matchs where, you know, each runner

00:28:40.861 --> 00:28:46.080
blazes off for glory, it ended up becoming
like one of these old time, guitar-picker

00:28:46.080 --> 00:28:50.241
battles, you know, where people sort of swap
chords back and forth and sort of learn from

00:28:50.241 --> 00:28:56.570
each other and then, gradually things build
and build and build until they're both competing

00:28:56.570 --> 00:29:00.670
with the same song, with the same techniques
back and forth -- that's what it became.

00:29:00.670 --> 00:29:06.950
Rather than "Americans vs. Indians", it became
two groups learning from each other, and then,

00:29:06.950 --> 00:29:08.080
once they had adopted each other's techniques,
then going at it.

00:29:08.080 --> 00:29:15.410
And by the time I got back, I felt like I
was on to something much deeper and broader

00:29:15.410 --> 00:29:18.890
and more complex than I ever imagined.
It was not about a sport.

00:29:18.890 --> 00:29:25.050
It was really about a way of life -- about
how this human animal has developed and what

00:29:25.050 --> 00:29:29.140
it's meant to be.
And I'm always left with this analogy about,

00:29:29.140 --> 00:29:32.501
you know -- you take an animal and you stick
it in a zoo and look what happens, you know?

00:29:32.501 --> 00:29:38.050
That animal becomes kind of antisocial and
grumpy and lethargic and sexually dysfunctional

00:29:38.050 --> 00:29:43.220
and has eating disorders and essentially -- I
don't want to point any fingers, but -- like

00:29:43.220 --> 00:29:45.780
us, you know?
Then you take that animal out, and you put

00:29:45.780 --> 00:29:49.930
it back into its natural setting -- where
it's designed to do all these mechanisms are

00:29:49.930 --> 00:29:53.030
meant for -- and suddenly, it's a whole different
creature, you know?

00:29:53.030 --> 00:29:59.340
Much less aggressive, much less cannibalistic,
not competing against its species, but with

00:29:59.340 --> 00:30:03.590
its species. Much calmer.
And that's what I think we found ourselves

00:30:03.590 --> 00:30:07.330
today, you know?
We forget that we are, you know, all this

00:30:07.330 --> 00:30:10.430
great digital stuff around us, but we're basically
animals.

00:30:10.430 --> 00:30:16.100
And if that animal gets an opportunity to
use its body the way it was intended, things

00:30:16.100 --> 00:30:19.830
fall into place.
When we lose that opportunity, then we start

00:30:19.830 --> 00:30:23.300
to have problems.
And we can dismiss the Tarahumara as being

00:30:23.300 --> 00:30:30.270
this kind of quirky, funky, ancient, indigenous
tribe that has nothing to do with us.

00:30:30.270 --> 00:30:34.380
Or, we can look at them and say, you know,
"Let's be humble and realize that there are

00:30:34.380 --> 00:30:38.700
some serious transferable skills that we need
to look for, or else we're going to continue

00:30:38.700 --> 00:30:41.590
to suffer the consequences that we see all
around us today."

00:30:41.590 --> 00:30:44.930
So thanks a lot guys.
I hope that was worthwhile.

00:30:44.930 --> 00:30:47.090
And if you have any questions, fire away.

00:30:47.090 --> 00:30:48.090
