00:30:48.090 --> 00:30:50.090
Chris McDougall: Yeah.

00:30:50.090 --> 00:30:51.090
&gt;&gt; [pause]

00:30:51.090 --> 00:30:57.610
Chris McDougall: He's telling me how handsome
I am.

00:30:57.610 --> 00:31:04.400
&gt;&gt; Could you use the mic to for questions?
It's right over there.

00:31:04.400 --> 00:31:08.360
Chris McDougall: I'm doing fine without you.

00:31:08.360 --> 00:31:09.360
&gt;&gt; [pause]

00:31:09.360 --> 00:31:14.590
Chris McDougall: You're talking about my good
looks and _______

00:31:14.590 --> 00:31:20.490
Q I was saying I got a chance to read the
book and found it wonderful as a historian,

00:31:20.490 --> 00:31:21.490
as a running inspiration, as a runner who's
marvelous in that respect.

00:31:21.490 --> 00:31:26.950
One of the parts of the book is quite sad
is that, any observation of the Tarahumara

00:31:26.950 --> 00:31:32.410
is going to impact on them.
And I was interested to know, What's happened

00:31:32.410 --> 00:31:35.060
to them since the book's come out?
And the attention that may have been drawn

00:31:35.060 --> 00:31:36.690
to them as a result of the book?

00:31:36.690 --> 00:31:40.990
Chris McDougall: Yeah, that's a great question.
And it's exactly the question that Caballo

00:31:40.990 --> 00:31:48.060
wrestled with for a long time before he decided
to launch this race.

00:31:48.060 --> 00:31:51.190
You know, the Tarahumara have voluntarily
lived in seclusion.

00:31:51.190 --> 00:31:54.600
That's the way they wanted it.
And so, to have some arrogant outsider show

00:31:54.600 --> 00:31:56.560
up and say, "Here's what you need is this
race."

00:31:56.560 --> 00:32:01.870
Caballo always said, "They don't need anything.
They're doing fine on their own."

00:32:01.870 --> 00:32:06.130
He offered to them; they accepted.
If they weren't interested, they would not

00:32:06.130 --> 00:32:09.970
turn up for the race.
Caballo's thinking is, "Look, they're backs

00:32:09.970 --> 00:32:12.930
are against the wall.
The Mexican government keeps pushing roads

00:32:12.930 --> 00:32:15.810
in here.
The drug cartels are dominating the region.

00:32:15.810 --> 00:32:21.050
It's a great place to grow drugs, because
you can't get helicopters or SUVs down there,

00:32:21.050 --> 00:32:26.260
so drug enforcement can't get down there.
You can grab the Tarahumara and dragoon them

00:32:26.260 --> 00:32:30.680
into carrying drugs out of the canyon.
Six bodies a week were turning up in the canyon

00:32:30.680 --> 00:32:35.370
being tossed off the edges of the cliffs.
So Caballo's thought was, "Look, yeah. This

00:32:35.370 --> 00:32:39.690
is a gamble. This is a risk.
But, it's an appreciable risk, because the

00:32:39.690 --> 00:32:47.640
payoff could be this validation of the Tarahumara
as the custodians of this lost art.

00:32:47.640 --> 00:32:52.650
That maybe he could turn into sort of this
U.N. sort of cultural buffer zone around them,

00:32:52.650 --> 00:32:59.350
where their techniques will be appreciated,
and that area will be sealed off and left

00:32:59.350 --> 00:33:04.070
for them to run in.
So, it's definitely a gamble, and he recognizes

00:33:04.070 --> 00:33:05.550
that.
And he's not convinced he's doing the right

00:33:05.550 --> 00:33:11.030
thing, but he hopes so.

00:33:11.030 --> 00:33:13.731
Q Thank you.

00:33:13.731 --> 00:33:14.731
Chris McDougall: Sure thing.

00:33:14.731 --> 00:33:15.731
&gt;&gt; [pause]

00:33:15.731 --> 00:33:18.110
Q You mentioned a unique style of running.
Can you describe it, or show it to us?

00:33:18.110 --> 00:33:19.110
Chris McDougall: Oh. The way they run?

00:33:19.110 --> 00:33:20.110
Q Yeah.

00:33:20.110 --> 00:33:22.320
Chris McDougall: Yeah. And I'll tell you,
if you had a five-year-old here, he could

00:33:22.320 --> 00:33:28.230
show you a lot better than I can.
It's bizarre how complicated we make the simple

00:33:28.230 --> 00:33:31.080
thing.
You know, when you think about all the animals

00:33:31.080 --> 00:33:33.880
on Earth.
There's only two that wear shoes -- us, and

00:33:33.880 --> 00:33:36.110
the ones we hold down and nail it to their
feet.

00:33:36.110 --> 00:33:39.370
Nobody else wears shoes.
No other animal wears shoes, and yet, they

00:33:39.370 --> 00:33:42.570
seem to do just fine.
Kids could give a crap what's on their feet,

00:33:42.570 --> 00:33:47.710
and they do just fine.
The way you run naturally is to run just like

00:33:47.710 --> 00:33:51.290
any kid does.
Or put it this way, if you take your shoes

00:33:51.290 --> 00:33:55.460
off right now and you go outside on the sidewalk,
you will learn how to run efficiently really

00:33:55.460 --> 00:33:57.620
fast.
Because any movement you do that hurts, you

00:33:57.620 --> 00:34:00.790
won't do twice.
And I can demonstrate if you want, but it's

00:34:00.790 --> 00:34:04.880
a real simple thing.
Basically, instead of using your heel -- Why

00:34:04.880 --> 00:34:09.290
on earth would you ever land on your heel?
If I jump off this thing on to the ground,

00:34:09.290 --> 00:34:15.690
the last thing I want to land on is my bony
heel with my legs straight.

00:34:15.690 --> 00:34:18.799
Running is essentially jumping. It's a series
of controlled jumps.

00:34:18.799 --> 00:34:22.190
So when you jump, you know, you want to land
on the balls of your feet and bend your knees

00:34:22.190 --> 00:34:26.159
for shock absorption. Real simple.
You can't bend your knees if your leg's in

00:34:26.159 --> 00:34:28.879
front of you.
You can't bend it if your heel's like this.

00:34:28.879 --> 00:34:33.980
That's painful. This is not painful.
So natural running technique is, essentially,

00:34:33.980 --> 00:34:38.279
to land on the ball of your foot, touch your
heel down, and lift the foot behind like that.

00:34:38.279 --> 00:34:41.919
It's all you're essentially doing is falling
forward through space -- kind of like you're

00:34:41.919 --> 00:34:46.869
like, belly-flopping into a pool or skydiving.
And, as you fall, you put a foot in front

00:34:46.869 --> 00:34:50.009
of you as you come around -- and that's it.
It's so simple.

00:34:50.009 --> 00:34:55.519
I can get everybody outside and, in ten minutes,
teach it to you and you can, you know, you'll

00:34:55.519 --> 00:34:59.319
have it mastered.
Does that help?

00:34:59.319 --> 00:35:00.579
Q Yep.

00:35:00.579 --> 00:35:06.730
Q Hi. Thank you.
I apologize if you answered these questions

00:35:06.730 --> 00:35:10.512
already, but I was wondering -- I've been
trying qi running lately, and my calfs are

00:35:10.512 --> 00:35:11.512
burning, so I was wondering if you had any
suggestions there.

00:35:11.512 --> 00:35:15.109
And then, two was, Do you have any mantras,
because I've been trying effortless, but I

00:35:15.109 --> 00:35:17.589
wanted to hear what you think about.

00:35:17.589 --> 00:35:20.300
Chris McDougall: Yeah. There's a couple good
ones.

00:35:20.300 --> 00:35:23.880
The thing about the burning calfs is, take
a day off.

00:35:23.880 --> 00:35:27.721
You know, if you go to the gym today and tomorrow
you're sore, take a day off.

00:35:27.721 --> 00:35:32.410
I think the thing with running is, people
are expecting pain -- they're expecting it

00:35:32.410 --> 00:35:36.029
to hurt -- and, at the first sign of pain,
they assume that's an injury.

00:35:36.029 --> 00:35:37.930
That's not an injury; that's just muscular
soreness.

00:35:37.930 --> 00:35:43.309
So yeah qi is really good.
So is pose, evolution -- all these running

00:35:43.309 --> 00:35:46.489
methods which are teaching to run the ball
of your foot are fine.

00:35:46.489 --> 00:35:49.960
Just be patient with it.
I think -- the best advice I got was from

00:35:49.960 --> 00:35:54.819
a guy named Barefoot Ken Bob, who said, "The
best way to learn is to let your feet tell

00:35:54.819 --> 00:35:57.490
you."
The problem with trying to learn how to run

00:35:57.490 --> 00:36:00.569
with your shoes on is, you're not getting
any feedback.

00:36:00.569 --> 00:36:02.071
So when you do something wrong, you're not
sure.

00:36:02.071 --> 00:36:04.720
You're constantly trying to sort of second
guess what your body is doing.

00:36:04.720 --> 00:36:08.329
When you're in your bare feet like, you know
instantly that's right or wrong.

00:36:08.329 --> 00:36:10.710
So I would say -- Are you using shoes to -- ?

00:36:10.710 --> 00:36:11.710
Q Yes. [laughing]

00:36:11.710 --> 00:36:13.839
Chris McDougall: Take them off. Honestly,
take them off.

00:36:13.839 --> 00:36:19.150
I was very slow -- I had to break a toe and
couldn't get my feet into shoes before I learned

00:36:19.150 --> 00:36:22.000
that lesson.
And then, when I tried to run with that broken

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:26.170
toe, I had to go barefoot.
The difference is unbelievable -- the amount

00:36:26.170 --> 00:36:30.359
of feedback you get.
If your posture is a little bit off in shoes,

00:36:30.359 --> 00:36:33.309
you don't notice it.
In your feet, it hurts. So you just change.

00:36:33.309 --> 00:36:36.299
You become much more erect.
Your feet's down underneath your hips.

00:36:36.299 --> 00:36:39.829
So, number one, I would definitely go barefoot
to practice.

00:36:39.829 --> 00:36:46.299
Number two, again, something else Barefoot
Ken Bob said is that, "When in doubt, relax."

00:36:46.299 --> 00:36:49.470
If your stiffness or soreness, you are tense
somewhere.

00:36:49.470 --> 00:36:54.099
Just sag into it, relax, breathe out.
Your body should feel light and weightless.

00:36:54.099 --> 00:36:58.430
I mean, kids love the feeling of weightlessness.
And if you ever want to see if a motion is

00:36:58.430 --> 00:37:02.460
biomechanically efficient, figure out whether
a kid or a boxer does it. You know?

00:37:02.460 --> 00:37:05.849
You watch boxers, how they move -- light and
loose, bouncing, right?

00:37:05.849 --> 00:37:08.750
Same with kids.
Kids love to be on trampolines and swings

00:37:08.750 --> 00:37:11.420
and things like that.
They like to feel weightless, and your running

00:37:11.420 --> 00:37:14.670
should feel the same way.
So, when in doubt, relax.

00:37:14.670 --> 00:37:19.349
Caballo's thing was "easy, light, smooth,
and fast."

00:37:19.349 --> 00:37:23.069
Focus on 'easy' first, because if that's all
you get, that ain't so bad.

00:37:23.069 --> 00:37:27.849
Then work on 'light', then 'smooth', and when
you have all those three things, then worry

00:37:27.849 --> 00:37:30.099
about 'fast'.
Most people do the opposite.

00:37:30.099 --> 00:37:34.990
They go with 'fast' first, and then try to
make it easy. He says, "Reverse that."

00:37:34.990 --> 00:37:36.190
So good luck.

00:37:36.190 --> 00:37:37.390
Q Any mantra?

00:37:37.390 --> 00:37:42.519
Chris McDougall: You know, pretty much not.
Those things, "When in doubt, relax."

00:37:42.519 --> 00:37:47.349
"Easy, light, smooth and fast."
But, I just find running -- yeah, I just do

00:37:47.349 --> 00:37:50.849
it, you know?
I just sort of see what's out there and have

00:37:50.849 --> 00:37:52.759
a good time.
Sure, thanks.

00:37:52.759 --> 00:37:55.490
Q Hi. I thought your book was excellent.

00:37:55.490 --> 00:37:56.490
Chris McDougall: Thanks.

00:37:56.490 --> 00:38:00.509
Q It was very inspiring as a runner.
In the book, you speak a lot about the Running

00:38:00.509 --> 00:38:03.559
Man Theory, about why we run -- or why we
originally ran.

00:38:03.559 --> 00:38:07.410
Could you just elaborate on that maybe a little
bit for people that haven't read the book?

00:38:07.410 --> 00:38:11.680
Chris McDougall: Yeah. I was debating whether
to get into that in this talk too, but it

00:38:11.680 --> 00:38:17.940
can sort of octopus out in so many directions.
But it's essentially this.

00:38:17.940 --> 00:38:23.599
The idea of the Running Man Theory is that,
you know, running is not something we just

00:38:23.599 --> 00:38:28.809
sort of picked up like we developed bungee
jumping or triathlons or cycling.

00:38:28.809 --> 00:38:31.650
Running is actually what we are genetically
designed to do.

00:38:31.650 --> 00:38:34.970
It is our number one, dominant characteristic
as an animal.

00:38:34.970 --> 00:38:40.839
And it's based on a couple of mysteries in
human history which have never been solved.

00:38:40.839 --> 00:38:44.210
Number one is this one too.
Two million years ago, the human brain exploded

00:38:44.210 --> 00:38:46.710
in size, you know.
Australopithecus had this tiny, little, peanut

00:38:46.710 --> 00:38:48.839
brain.
And suddenly, we get these big old, melon

00:38:48.839 --> 00:38:53.680
heads about two million years ago.
You can only support a brain of that size

00:38:53.680 --> 00:38:59.609
if that organism has a regular source of dense
caloric energy.

00:38:59.609 --> 00:39:04.900
Essentially, homo erectus was eating dead
animals, having animal protein -- scientific

00:39:04.900 --> 00:39:07.259
fact.
Two million years ago, we're eating dead animals.

00:39:07.259 --> 00:39:11.660
The only problem is, the first weapon only
appeared 200,000 years ago.

00:39:11.660 --> 00:39:15.480
So somehow, you've got a gap with about two
million years -- somehow we're getting food

00:39:15.480 --> 00:39:18.839
with no weapons to kill the animals.
We're obviously not using our like, little

00:39:18.839 --> 00:39:20.549
sissy weapons, because we've got nothing,
you know?

00:39:20.549 --> 00:39:22.940
We got no claws, no fangs, no strength, no
speed.

00:39:22.940 --> 00:39:28.369
I mean, Usain Bolt is the fastest human in
history, and a squirrel can outrun Usain Bolt.

00:39:28.369 --> 00:39:34.569
[laughter] So how are we getting these dead
animals with no weapons?

00:39:34.569 --> 00:39:39.380
The Running Man Theory is, we were essentially
running animals to death -- that, what made

00:39:39.380 --> 00:39:44.109
human life viable two million years ago -- and
for a long time -- was the fact that we had

00:39:44.109 --> 00:39:47.200
these unique characteristics as long distance
runners.

00:39:47.200 --> 00:39:53.470
We were hunting pack animals.
Most animals vent heat by respiration -- they

00:39:53.470 --> 00:39:56.990
breathe it out.
We vent heat predominantly by perspiration.

00:39:56.990 --> 00:40:00.209
Which means that, if you're running against
a horse, at about ten miles, that horse has

00:40:00.209 --> 00:40:01.400
a choice.
It's either going to breathe or it's going

00:40:01.400 --> 00:40:05.740
to cool off, but it ain't doing both.
We can.

00:40:05.740 --> 00:40:09.049
There's a lot of other sort of physiological
components of this.

00:40:09.049 --> 00:40:17.940
What I find most intriguing about the Running
Man Theory is that the way we do this is not

00:40:17.940 --> 00:40:20.140
an individual.
You don't go up by yourself and run an animal

00:40:20.140 --> 00:40:21.180
to death.
It had to be a pack.

00:40:21.180 --> 00:40:25.921
The pack has to hunt together.
It's the only way it's going to work, which

00:40:25.921 --> 00:40:30.869
means old people, young people, men and women.
And what you find is that, if that theory

00:40:30.869 --> 00:40:37.350
is true, it essentially gives you a culture
much like the Tarahumara.

00:40:37.350 --> 00:40:42.150
The hunting pack theory to be accurate, that
means that old people can run as well as young

00:40:42.150 --> 00:40:45.200
people.
And that's actually born out by marathon finishing

00:40:45.200 --> 00:40:48.529
times.
People who are in their 60's are still running

00:40:48.529 --> 00:40:51.339
the same speed they were running back when
they were 19, 20 years old.

00:40:51.339 --> 00:40:56.650
You don't lose your top-end speed in endurance
contests for 45 years, unlike any other physical

00:40:56.650 --> 00:40:59.089
activity.
You get into long distances, you know -- women

00:40:59.089 --> 00:41:03.660
as sprinters, you guys suck; you're the worst.
There's not a fast woman sprinter ever.

00:41:03.660 --> 00:41:07.349
There are high school kids today that can
beat the fastest woman of all time.

00:41:07.349 --> 00:41:13.190
Even as milers, you guys are worse than mediocre.
The fastest woman miler did a 4:15.

00:41:13.190 --> 00:41:17.680
Again, I could throw a rock and hit a high
school boy somewhere in New York who can run

00:41:17.680 --> 00:41:21.329
faster than 4:15.
But, you get to 50-miles or a hundred miles,

00:41:21.329 --> 00:41:25.560
and suddenly, it's anybody's game.
The top female ultra marathoners can beat

00:41:25.560 --> 00:41:34.289
any guy on the planet in a head-to-head contest.
Emily Baer, back in 2008, was in the Hard

00:41:34.289 --> 00:41:39.220
Rock 100, one of the toughest 100-mile races.
She finished in the top ten while stopping

00:41:39.220 --> 00:41:44.339
to breast-feed her baby at the aid stations.
[laughter] So she beat basically 500 of the

00:41:44.339 --> 00:41:49.070
best, male, ultra runners on planet Earth,
while breast-feeding her kid on a super-hard

00:41:49.070 --> 00:41:52.569
100-mile course.
So you have all these little bits of circumstantial

00:41:52.569 --> 00:41:55.690
evidence out there.
The fact that, as distances get longer, women

00:41:55.690 --> 00:42:01.569
get stronger, that old guys never lose their
top-end speed, that we vent this heat, that

00:42:01.569 --> 00:42:08.499
we have all this elastic recoil in our legs.
All those things add up to a picture of humans

00:42:08.499 --> 00:42:12.099
as being designed to be basically like a pack
of dogs, you know?

00:42:12.099 --> 00:42:16.499
When you live like that pack of dogs, you
can't be greedy, you can't be covetous, you

00:42:16.499 --> 00:42:20.849
can't hold grudges and be pissed off at the
other guy, because you've got to function

00:42:20.849 --> 00:42:24.450
as a pack.
Essentially, that left us with what the Tarahumara

00:42:24.450 --> 00:42:26.830
still are today.

00:42:26.830 --> 00:42:27.830
Q Thanks.

00:42:27.830 --> 00:42:29.460
Chris McDougall: Sure thing.

00:42:29.460 --> 00:42:33.599
Q Hi. I have two questions, actually.
One is, Are there any similarities between

00:42:33.599 --> 00:42:39.890
the Tarahumara and other tribes known for
running, like the Kenyans are very famous

00:42:39.890 --> 00:42:42.720
runners and others.
Have you studied them?

00:42:42.720 --> 00:42:43.990
And are there similarities?

00:42:43.990 --> 00:42:48.030
Chris McDougall: Yeah. What's kind of cool
about this Running Man Theory is that -- it

00:42:48.030 --> 00:42:52.279
was both cool and vexing at the same time
 -- when these anthropologists at Utah and

00:42:52.279 --> 00:42:56.410
Harvard developed this theory that humans
ran animals to death.

00:42:56.410 --> 00:42:59.970
You know, anything is great in theory.
I can have a theory that "if you flap your

00:42:59.970 --> 00:43:02.509
arms, you're going to fly," but you got to
find someone who can actually do it, or else

00:43:02.509 --> 00:43:07.730
the theory ain't worth a damn.
So if humans are physiologically capable in

00:43:07.730 --> 00:43:10.849
theory of running an animal to death, there
should be some human out there somewhere on

00:43:10.849 --> 00:43:14.480
planet Earth that can do it.
And they actually found them in the Kalahari

00:43:14.480 --> 00:43:17.440
bushmen -- to this day still do the same thing.
They still run animals to death.

00:43:17.440 --> 00:43:23.611
And you find tales throughout all -- basically
every indigenous culture on the planet -- the

00:43:23.611 --> 00:43:27.329
aborigines, the Hopi Indians, the Navahos,
the Seris.

00:43:27.329 --> 00:43:30.740
Around the planet, there are all tales of
people who ran animals to death.

00:43:30.740 --> 00:43:35.609
To this day, Hopi and Navaho still have long
running rituals and traditions.

00:43:35.609 --> 00:43:42.549
So, yeah, there are sort of markers throughout
the planet of people who still practice the

00:43:42.549 --> 00:43:43.900
same things.
You mentioned that the Kenyans there -- one

00:43:43.900 --> 00:43:46.710
thing I should be sure to distinguish.
A lot of times people say to me, "Yeah. Listen,

00:43:46.710 --> 00:43:51.460
if these guys are such hot shit, how come
they're not winning the Olympic marathon?"

00:43:51.460 --> 00:43:57.819
You know, Kenyans have become specialists
at a really artificial form of running.

00:43:57.819 --> 00:44:02.150
We've taken an endurance event -- the marathon
 -- we've basically turned it into a sprint.

00:44:02.150 --> 00:44:06.301
They have -- same way Jamaicans are very good
at sprinting, and guys from Lake Placid are

00:44:06.301 --> 00:44:13.319
very good at bobsledding -- Kenyans have taken
certain natural and geographical advantages

00:44:13.319 --> 00:44:19.720
and made themselves specialists in a real,
artificial form of competition.

00:44:19.720 --> 00:44:25.160
So if you took a bunch of Tarahumara and dropped
them off in the Rift Valley among the Nandi,

00:44:25.160 --> 00:44:28.760
you know, would they run as fast as the Kenyans?
Probably, if they cared to.

00:44:28.760 --> 00:44:32.670
But, the Kenyans are really essentially no
different than anybody else.

00:44:32.670 --> 00:44:35.799
Physiologically, they're the same.
They're just better, and they work harder

00:44:35.799 --> 00:44:38.930
at doing what we could all do.
Another question, Bill?

00:44:38.930 --> 00:44:42.400
Q Yeah, so. I've been experimenting with barefoot
running.

00:44:42.400 --> 00:44:46.369
And actually, I feel it's like much more fun
than normal running, because you get a lot

00:44:46.369 --> 00:44:49.579
of sensation in your feet.
But sometimes like, all the sidewalks in my

00:44:49.579 --> 00:44:53.970
neighborhood are like this super-bumpy like
kind of gravelly sidewalk, and it's actually

00:44:53.970 --> 00:44:57.019
very painful.
So I find that like, I can't even really run

00:44:57.019 --> 00:44:59.660
in my neighborhood.
If you are running barefoot, like what do

00:44:59.660 --> 00:45:04.029
you do when you encounter surfaces like that?

00:45:04.029 --> 00:45:06.930
Chris McDougall: Yeah, I mean you can buy
these things too.

00:45:06.930 --> 00:45:08.109
Have you seen these things?

00:45:08.109 --> 00:45:09.749
Q Yeah, that's what I have actually.

00:45:09.749 --> 00:45:11.549
Chris McDougall: And these are too painful
for you?

00:45:11.549 --> 00:45:15.420
Q No, no. It's fine with that. I was just
wondering if there's a way to go fully barefoot.

00:45:15.420 --> 00:45:18.740
Chris McDougall: Yeah. I mean, I do.
Where I live out in the _____ of Pennsylvania,

00:45:18.740 --> 00:45:23.940
it's all paved, asphalt farm roads.
What I do sometimes, if I'm heading off somewhere

00:45:23.940 --> 00:45:27.880
where I don't know what kind of road's ahead,
I'll just jam a pair of these in the back

00:45:27.880 --> 00:45:33.440
of my shorts, and so I'll run in my bare feet,
you hit something painful, jam these on, keep

00:45:33.440 --> 00:45:35.279
running, and take them off again.
And think about it too, it's not a question

00:45:35.279 --> 00:45:40.170
of, you know, "shoes vs. bare feet".
It's a question of what your shoes are doing

00:45:40.170 --> 00:45:43.339
to your feet.
And, you know, protection is fine up until

00:45:43.339 --> 00:45:47.319
the point where the protection starts to dominate
and control what your foot's doing.

00:45:47.319 --> 00:45:52.420
But some kind of minimal protection of your
feet, you know, Ice Age cavemen were wearing

00:45:52.420 --> 00:45:56.390
their own handcrafted shoes.
So I think that's fine.

00:45:56.390 --> 00:46:01.199
My beef is with these like, big, supportive,
motion control -- just the fact 'motion control'

00:46:01.199 --> 00:46:05.569
 -- if you hear that word, stay the hell away.
That's my beef with those kind of shoes.

00:46:05.569 --> 00:46:06.569
Q Thanks.

00:46:06.569 --> 00:46:07.569
Chris McDougall: Sure thing. Anybody else?
Yep.

00:46:07.569 --> 00:46:11.609
Q I just like to say thanks for writing the
book.

00:46:11.609 --> 00:46:17.519
I read it back in June, and at that point,
I was on the verge of quitting running, because

00:46:17.519 --> 00:46:23.089
I've had so many chronic injuries.
Since I read that, I went and found a pose

00:46:23.089 --> 00:46:26.299
coach.
Last several months I've been training -- completely

00:46:26.299 --> 00:46:29.039
transformed -- miraculously, all of those
chronic injuries have just disappeared.

00:46:29.039 --> 00:46:32.220
Actually, I've been training with Lee Saxby,
who I think you know, in London.

00:46:32.220 --> 00:46:36.559
Chris McDougall: Oh yeah. So you have been
training with Lee Saxby?

00:46:36.559 --> 00:46:39.720
Q Yeah. Actually I have been training sessions
with Lee just last weekend.

00:46:39.720 --> 00:46:41.960
Chris McDougall: Oh, good. He's fabulous.

00:46:41.960 --> 00:46:45.200
Q Straight away. I think the same thing happened
to you?

00:46:45.200 --> 00:46:49.460
He sort of video-ed me 30 seconds, knew what
the problem was.

00:46:49.460 --> 00:46:52.059
Chris McDougall: Mind if I interrupt you and
tell this story?

00:46:52.059 --> 00:46:54.170
Do you mind if I interrupt you and tell them
this story?

00:46:54.170 --> 00:46:55.170
Q Oh, no. No. Please go ahead.

00:46:55.170 --> 00:46:59.290
Chris McDougall: Hang on. The one time I've
gotten injured in the past couple of years

00:46:59.290 --> 00:47:02.329
was the time I went back to wearing shoes.
I thought, "Okay, now I run like Caballo,

00:47:02.329 --> 00:47:07.930
I am technologically perfect. I am invulnerable."
I put on a pair of shoes, because we've got

00:47:07.930 --> 00:47:11.319
a lot of snow in Pennsylvania.
And a couple weeks later, I've got this big,

00:47:11.319 --> 00:47:14.362
blinding heel pain.
What in the hell's going on, because I'm on

00:47:14.362 --> 00:47:18.579
the verge of publishing this book about how
you can run injury-free forever -- friggin'

00:47:18.579 --> 00:47:21.400
injured. [laughter]
And I went back to the usual routine, went

00:47:21.400 --> 00:47:24.619
back to the sports medicine doctors and the
podiatrists and they told me the same old

00:47:24.619 --> 00:47:29.150
bullshit that does not work, you know?
"Roll your foot on the golf ball, stretch

00:47:29.150 --> 00:47:35.440
the calf, wear an ice plant."
I mean, it's bizarre to me that plantar fasciitis

00:47:35.440 --> 00:47:40.130
is as prevalent -- it's like chlamydia, and
nobody can get rid of this thing.

00:47:40.130 --> 00:47:42.559
And these guys just keep dishing out the same
old stuff.

00:47:42.559 --> 00:47:46.630
It does not work.
I happened to be in London -- to actually

00:47:46.630 --> 00:47:49.690
go to a seminar -- and someone told me, "Yeah,
you should go see this guy, Lee Saxby. He's

00:47:49.690 --> 00:47:52.839
a running coach."
I'm like, "You understand? I'm perfect. I'm

00:47:52.839 --> 00:47:55.260
the perfect runner.
I've got no problem with my technique. It's

00:47:55.260 --> 00:47:58.759
something else."
I go to see this dude, and he's a smart-ass

00:47:58.759 --> 00:48:01.920
Brit. [laughter]
And he's like, "Let me see your run."

00:48:01.920 --> 00:48:04.329
And I'm like, "All right, fine."
So I run down the sidewalk.

00:48:04.329 --> 00:48:08.920
He videotaped me for like, literally, 30 seconds.
I run from like here to there and back.

00:48:08.920 --> 00:48:12.589
He snapped shut the viewfinder, and he's like,
"Okay, you're cured. Problem solved."

00:48:12.589 --> 00:48:16.049
I've had this problem now for six months.
I've tried everything.

00:48:16.049 --> 00:48:19.230
So I go, "All right, what is it?"
He's like, "Describe to me the way you run."

00:48:19.230 --> 00:48:21.819
So I described, you know, the perfect Tarahumara
running technique.

00:48:21.819 --> 00:48:25.430
And he's like, "Yeah, look at this."
And he shows me the video.

00:48:25.430 --> 00:48:27.599
I'm doing the exact opposite of what I think
I'm doing.

00:48:27.599 --> 00:48:32.089
You know, I think I'm leaning forward, with
my feet under my hips, on the ball of my foot.

00:48:32.089 --> 00:48:36.009
Instead, I'm way back here.
My body weight is over my heels, not over

00:48:36.009 --> 00:48:40.009
my hips.
I'm leveraging my body over my ankles like

00:48:40.009 --> 00:48:42.289
that.
And I'm not landing on my forefoot; I'm landing

00:48:42.289 --> 00:48:44.150
on my heel.
But I couldn't sense it.

00:48:44.150 --> 00:48:47.569
To me, it felt like forefoot is actually banging
on my heel.

00:48:47.569 --> 00:48:53.220
This dude -- hand before God -- you know,
I know it sounded some bizarre, evangelistic,

00:48:53.220 --> 00:48:57.950
'demons be gone' baloney -- this dude cured
me in and out.

00:48:57.950 --> 00:49:00.150
I walked out the door, and the heel pain was
gone.

00:49:00.150 --> 00:49:04.509
It has never come back.
So this is the guy we're talking about -- this

00:49:04.509 --> 00:49:05.509
guy, Lee Saxby.

00:49:05.509 --> 00:49:06.660
Q I had the same kind of thing.
I've been training with a pose coach for four

00:49:06.660 --> 00:49:09.700
months now, but I had this problem with calf
pain, and Lee did the exact same thing.

00:49:09.700 --> 00:49:14.109
He did it with me in 30 seconds.
That I was bending at the hip, not at the

00:49:14.109 --> 00:49:19.809
ankles.
Anyway, but that was my question.

00:49:19.809 --> 00:49:26.200
So, it's fair to say that I'm very bought
into this idea of us being evolved to run

00:49:26.200 --> 00:49:33.740
and to do it in a natural way.
I'm testing the Paleo Diet and these kinds

00:49:33.740 --> 00:49:36.900
of things.
There's one thing that sort of concerns me

00:49:36.900 --> 00:49:42.849
about sort of ultra running and ultra distance
events, anything that would be considered

00:49:42.849 --> 00:49:46.769
ultra.
I've read a few things from some -- the guy

00:49:46.769 --> 00:49:54.190
that says evolutionary fitness, primal blueprints.
Some of these guys are also -- have these

00:49:54.190 --> 00:49:56.720
similar ideas that we should train in the
way that [inaudible]

00:49:56.720 --> 00:49:57.720
Chris McDougall: Is that Archivanie?

00:49:57.720 --> 00:50:01.220
Q Yeah, I think that was the guy. I think
he recently posted an article.

00:50:01.220 --> 00:50:05.700
I thought it was questionable, but I wanted
to see what you thought -- that marathon running

00:50:05.700 --> 00:50:08.779
is bad for you.
And he cited a few things.

00:50:08.779 --> 00:50:15.200
A couple things that concern me -- it's damaging
to the liver, it's damaging to the kidneys.

00:50:15.200 --> 00:50:21.890
So the question is, you know, At what point
are we doing things that are artificial like,

00:50:21.890 --> 00:50:24.829
you know, running a marathon is not something
that we were evolved for.

00:50:24.829 --> 00:50:30.160
That's highly unlikely scenario in a hunter-gatherer.
You know, you wouldn't just run flat out for

00:50:30.160 --> 00:50:36.400
26-miles or whatever it was.
So have you any ideas as to, What is a good

00:50:36.400 --> 00:50:42.750
way to tackle ultra events, you know?
Is it to do with intensity?

00:50:42.750 --> 00:50:48.940
Is it to do with the distance, you know?
And do you have any thoughts about it's potentially

00:50:48.940 --> 00:50:49.940
damaging beyond your mechanics [undecipherable]?

00:50:49.940 --> 00:50:56.930
Chris McDougall: Yeah, it's a great question.
I mean, I think I'm not actually a big fan

00:50:56.930 --> 00:51:02.599
of big, urban marathons, for that reason.
Because it really creates like, this 'moral

00:51:02.599 --> 00:51:06.470
obligation' to do more than you may want to
 -- or are ready for.

00:51:06.470 --> 00:51:10.200
I mean, nowadays, if you start to run, you
make the mistake of telling anybody that you're

00:51:10.200 --> 00:51:11.880
running, the first question out of their mouth
is going to be, "Have you run a marathon?

00:51:11.880 --> 00:51:16.514
When are you going to run a marathon?
How fast can you run a marathon?" You know?

00:51:16.514 --> 00:51:21.739
And if you tell them you did a 4-hour marathon
as opposed to 3:59.59 like -- one's great

00:51:21.739 --> 00:51:25.809
and one sucks.
Who gives a shit? Who cares?

00:51:25.809 --> 00:51:30.680
This emphasis on doing this arbitrary distance
in this arbitrary amount of time -- I think

00:51:30.680 --> 00:51:36.550
it forces people beyond their capabilities.
I mean, if you're learning how to swim, you

00:51:36.550 --> 00:51:38.640
know?
They don't put you in a pool and show you

00:51:38.640 --> 00:51:40.660
doggie-paddle and go, "Have you swum English
Channel?

00:51:40.660 --> 00:51:43.819
When are you going to swim English Channel?
How fast can you swim the English Channel?"

00:51:43.819 --> 00:51:46.060
You learn how to swim gradually.
It's fun first.

00:51:46.060 --> 00:51:48.670
You go off the sliding board and off the diving
board.

00:51:48.670 --> 00:51:52.829
You play Marco Polo.
And I wish people would learn how to run the

00:51:52.829 --> 00:51:58.260
way they learn how to swim.
One thing about distance running is -- and

00:51:58.260 --> 00:52:02.150
I made this distinction between the way the
Tarahumara run and the way the Kenyans run

00:52:02.150 --> 00:52:04.369
marathons.
You know, we are endurance animals.

00:52:04.369 --> 00:52:08.999
We are not fast. And yet, we emphasize speed
all the time, you know?

00:52:08.999 --> 00:52:11.999
A hundred yard dash, and How fast can you
do a marathon?

00:52:11.999 --> 00:52:17.970
We're not fast. Our strength is not running
like the animals we're trying to kill, you

00:52:17.970 --> 00:52:19.430
know?
If you make an animal -- if you try to make

00:52:19.430 --> 00:52:23.150
that animal run as fast as it can, as long
as it can until it dies -- if we do the same

00:52:23.150 --> 00:52:26.210
thing, we'd have two corpses out there on
this event.

00:52:26.210 --> 00:52:31.650
What we're really good at is, surge and recover,
surge and recover -- go hard and back off

00:52:31.650 --> 00:52:34.660
again.
It's funny, there's a guy named Jeff Galloway,

00:52:34.660 --> 00:52:39.499
who came up with this form of running marathons,
where you basically run ten minutes, and walk

00:52:39.499 --> 00:52:42.079
a minute -- run ten, walk one.
This guy gets blistered all the time.

00:52:42.079 --> 00:52:45.319
People are, "Agh, that's not running."
That's exactly what running is supposed to

00:52:45.319 --> 00:52:49.369
be, surge and recover.
So this whole question of whether marathons

00:52:49.369 --> 00:52:54.319
are damaging.
You know, I think the anthropological evidence

00:52:54.319 --> 00:52:58.549
is pretty strong that we evolved -- I mean,
for instance, to run an antelope to death

00:52:58.549 --> 00:53:01.299
 -- you know how long that takes?
Two to five hours.

00:53:01.299 --> 00:53:08.769
I mean, it's bizarre how the heat frustration
time for big game exactly correlates to the

00:53:08.769 --> 00:53:13.470
finishing times for marathon.
So, if you look down from, you know, Mars

00:53:13.470 --> 00:53:17.049
on November first, and you see like tens of
thousands of people running through Queens,

00:53:17.049 --> 00:53:19.229
I mean, it would look like some bizarre animal
panic.

00:53:19.229 --> 00:53:25.039
Yet, somehow we feel this atavistic desire
to gather in large groups and run for two

00:53:25.039 --> 00:53:29.819
to five hours.
So, my speculation -- it's not fact; it's

00:53:29.819 --> 00:53:32.420
speculation -- is that, this is what we're
designed to do.

00:53:32.420 --> 00:53:36.880
So, it's good for us.
But, through training and acclimation, and

00:53:36.880 --> 00:53:38.809
not just by, you know, moral obligation.

00:53:38.809 --> 00:53:48.789
Q But if you do it right and recover properly,
then there's no reason to -- those people

00:53:48.789 --> 00:53:52.319
maybe go to marathons without training [inaudible]

00:53:52.319 --> 00:53:56.309
Chris McDougall: Yeah. I mean, I like the
way -- I like the whole culture of ultra running.

00:53:56.309 --> 00:53:59.589
Even though people are running a hundred miles,
it's so much more relaxed.

00:53:59.589 --> 00:54:02.210
Nobody gives a crap how fast you run a hundred
miles.

00:54:02.210 --> 00:54:05.579
They can't believe you did it. [laughter]
So, you know?

00:54:05.579 --> 00:54:09.019
And the thing about ultras too, is again,
it's really kind of cool to the whole hunting

00:54:09.019 --> 00:54:11.239
pack thing.
You can't run an ultra by yourself.

00:54:11.239 --> 00:54:13.599
You need to have support there.
You need to have a pacer.

00:54:13.599 --> 00:54:17.609
You need to have friends waiting to give you
like M &amp; M's at the 15-mile mark.

00:54:17.609 --> 00:54:22.519
There's something very comforting and social
and group-oriented and non-competitive about

00:54:22.519 --> 00:54:25.999
ultras as opposed to marathons, which are
all about like -- [deet] [deet] [deet] [deet],

00:54:25.999 --> 00:54:28.990
you know, and like just sprint and pass the
other guy at the finish line, so.

00:54:28.990 --> 00:54:34.380
Again, I think Barefoot Ken Bob's advice is
the best, "when in doubt, relax" -- and you'll

00:54:34.380 --> 00:54:35.510
be fine.

00:54:35.510 --> 00:54:36.630
Q [inaudible]

00:54:36.630 --> 00:54:39.460
Chris McDougall: Sure. Thank you.

00:54:39.460 --> 00:54:44.809
Q Thanks for coming today.
So, you know, you've talked a lot about technique.

00:54:44.809 --> 00:54:47.299
And this is very important.
I've done Pose myself.

00:54:47.299 --> 00:54:53.660
I realize, you know -- video analysis, working
with a coach -- it's pretty critical to really

00:54:53.660 --> 00:54:57.309
making the shift away from being a heel-striker
to running naturally.

00:54:57.309 --> 00:55:03.650
Do you support any one program to do this?
Do you suggest, you know, a certain path that

00:55:03.650 --> 00:55:06.359
people go on to relearn how to run?

00:55:06.359 --> 00:55:07.529
Chris McDougall: Absolutely, buy this book,
number one.

00:55:07.529 --> 00:55:13.420
Step one. [laughter] -- in quantity.
No, I'm sorry, do you want to finish your

00:55:13.420 --> 00:55:14.420
question?

00:55:14.420 --> 00:55:16.170
Q Pose. Any other programs that are out there
that people do?

00:55:16.170 --> 00:55:19.510
Any of the certifications or seminars that
happen?

00:55:19.510 --> 00:55:23.119
Do you have any that you can recommend that
people do?

00:55:23.119 --> 00:55:27.400
Because, I think it sounds great that, you
know, this is a new way to run, but there

00:55:27.400 --> 00:55:32.569
is a significant amount of work that has to
be done for people really to relearn how to

00:55:32.569 --> 00:55:34.779
get off of, you know, running on their heels.

00:55:34.779 --> 00:55:36.729
Chris McDougall: Yeah, it's true.
There's a significant amount of work to be

00:55:36.729 --> 00:55:42.049
done, but it's unbelievable how quickly you
can do it.

00:55:42.049 --> 00:55:44.974
Are you guys familiar with the Pose method
that he's referring to?

00:55:44.974 --> 00:55:50.009
The Pose method was invented by a guy named
Dr. Nicholas Romanov, who was originally part

00:55:50.009 --> 00:55:55.660
of the Soviet Olympic sports training system.
And he was trying to answer the same questions

00:55:55.660 --> 00:55:58.430
like, You know, we've got every eye here.
We tell them to go faster or do this or that,

00:55:58.430 --> 00:56:00.989
but we never actually tell them how they're
supposed to run.

00:56:00.989 --> 00:56:05.059
And so, he started studying the physiology
and the biomechanics of runners.

00:56:05.059 --> 00:56:10.900
And what he found was that, all runners -- no
matter what the distance -- the fastest guys

00:56:10.900 --> 00:56:15.769
are always in the same pose at a certain point.
Like, you can freeze-frame Jesse Owens or

00:56:15.769 --> 00:56:19.710
Usain Bolt or Frank Schroeder -- any runner,
any distance, throughout history -- and at

00:56:19.710 --> 00:56:24.190
some point, they're going to have that leg
bent with the foot directly underneath the

00:56:24.190 --> 00:56:27.700
hips and leaning forward, letting gravity
pull them forward.

00:56:27.700 --> 00:56:32.680
This guy named Arthur Lydiard, the great New
Zealand coach, talked about pushers vs. pullers.

00:56:32.680 --> 00:56:36.950
And he could watch the start of a race -- hundreds
of guys in a cross-country race and he can

00:56:36.950 --> 00:56:39.890
go, "That guy ain't going to win. That guy
ain't going to win. That guy might win."

00:56:39.890 --> 00:56:43.390
And the reason why was, he was looking for
'pushers' vs. 'pullers'.

00:56:43.390 --> 00:56:48.089
Pushers are pushing off with muscular strength.
Pullers were just pulling their foot up as

00:56:48.089 --> 00:56:53.210
they fell forward through space.
So Romanov -- back in early 80's, maybe even

00:56:53.210 --> 00:56:55.839
earlier -- developed this running method called
the 'pose method'.

00:56:55.839 --> 00:56:59.720
And it's so stinking simple, you can't believe
it.

00:56:59.720 --> 00:57:02.819
I actually spent two days with Romanov down
in Florida.

00:57:02.819 --> 00:57:07.729
Spent one whole day, where he's explaining
all the physiology and the history and the

00:57:07.729 --> 00:57:09.069
antecedents.
And then, he took me outside to actually teach

00:57:09.069 --> 00:57:14.219
me the method, and it was like half an hour.
I mean, no other activity -- you know, you

00:57:14.219 --> 00:57:16.630
try and learn how to play tennis or to fence,
it takes weeks.

00:57:16.630 --> 00:57:21.359
This dude, in 30 minutes, can radically transform
your running style.

00:57:21.359 --> 00:57:27.890
But what I find is that pose, qi, evolution
running -- they're all essentially, I believe,

00:57:27.890 --> 00:57:31.059
the same thing.
The difficulty with those methods, though,

00:57:31.059 --> 00:57:36.220
is -- and I really wish I had listened to
Barefoot Ken Bob, all these barefoot dudes.

00:57:36.220 --> 00:57:39.730
You know, you kind of disregard them, because
they call themselves 'barefoot' something?

00:57:39.730 --> 00:57:41.710
[laughter]
Do you ever see Ken Bob, you know?

00:57:41.710 --> 00:57:45.089
The guy looks like a troll.
He's got this beard, and he's crazy-looking.

00:57:45.089 --> 00:57:50.789
But what these dudes said was, You need to
remove the obstacle for the feedback.

00:57:50.789 --> 00:57:54.839
You've got to take the shoes off, so.
I tried to learn qi and pose.

00:57:54.839 --> 00:58:01.029
What I had to do is, constantly mentally remind
myself of all the stuff I was doing.

00:58:01.029 --> 00:58:04.099
It was kind of this constant checklist of
body angles and stuff.

00:58:04.099 --> 00:58:06.069
But if you take your shoes off, you get that
instantly.

00:58:06.069 --> 00:58:10.380
So, if I were doing it all over again, I would
take the shoes off first, and then pick up

00:58:10.380 --> 00:58:13.190
any one of them.
Even CrossFit. Have any of you guys do CrossFit?

00:58:13.190 --> 00:58:15.849
Q Yeah, that's what I do.

00:58:15.849 --> 00:58:19.141
Chris McDougall: Yeah, I was going to tell
you.

00:58:19.141 --> 00:58:22.130
You can kick my ass. I'm sure you can.

00:58:22.130 --> 00:58:23.259
Q I went to a CrossFit CFE, CrossFit endurance
seminar last weekend, actually.

00:58:23.259 --> 00:58:25.109
Chris McDougall: Those guys actually have
the best "before and after" videos I've ever

00:58:25.109 --> 00:58:28.869
seen online for running.
You watch the 'before' and then 'after' and

00:58:28.869 --> 00:58:33.819
the transformation that these CrossFit coaches
do with runners is unbelievable.

00:58:33.819 --> 00:58:34.819
Q Yeah.

00:58:34.819 --> 00:58:37.759
Chris McDougall: Yeah, I think any one of
these styles, but the one difference I would

00:58:37.759 --> 00:58:40.329
make is, go bare.

00:58:40.329 --> 00:58:41.329
Q [inaudible]

00:58:41.329 --> 00:58:42.329
Chris McDougall: Sure. Thanks.

00:58:42.329 --> 00:58:43.751
&gt;&gt; So, we're right at time, but thank you.

00:58:43.751 --> 00:58:45.279
Chris McDougall: You got one person there?

00:58:45.279 --> 00:58:47.911
Q Sorry. I'll be really quick.
Thank you so much for coming today.

00:58:47.911 --> 00:58:48.911
Chris McDougall: Yeah, thank you.

00:58:48.911 --> 00:58:52.809
Q Very appreciative of having you.
I haven't read your book, but I was mesmerized

00:58:52.809 --> 00:58:56.069
and very inspired by your speech today.
You're an eloquent presenter, so thank you.

00:58:56.069 --> 00:58:57.069
Chris McDougall: Oh thanks.

00:58:57.069 --> 00:58:59.349
Q I just did my first half marathon last weekend
in Indianapolis.

00:58:59.349 --> 00:59:00.349
Chris McDougall: Great, great.

00:59:00.349 --> 00:59:03.000
Q And there was one guy running barefoot,
and he got all the attention, because everyone's

00:59:03.000 --> 00:59:05.529
like -- and he even told me, he was like,
"Take off your shoes."

00:59:05.529 --> 00:59:07.489
I'm like, "Are you crazy, dude? Like, what
are you talking about?"

00:59:07.489 --> 00:59:13.079
But, I'm just curious about how advertisers
 -- like a Nike -- is reacting to all this

00:59:13.079 --> 00:59:14.750
publicity.
I work in advertising, so I'm just kind of

00:59:14.750 --> 00:59:16.039
curious about -- like, when Supersize Me came
out, obviously McDonald's took a huge loss

00:59:16.039 --> 00:59:17.829
in revenue and cut, so I was just kind of
curious, have they'd approached you in Lancaster?

00:59:17.829 --> 00:59:23.349
Yay, I have family from there.
But, like kind of what it's been, in terms

00:59:23.349 --> 00:59:28.989
of all the publicity like kind of where it's
been at.

00:59:28.989 --> 00:59:32.109
Chris McDougall: Well, let me ask you, "What
would you do if you're facing this kind of

00:59:32.109 --> 00:59:36.401
crisis or this scandal as an advertiser/marketing
person? What would you do?"

00:59:36.401 --> 00:59:38.210
Q [laughing] If I was Nike?

00:59:38.210 --> 00:59:39.210
Chris McDougall: Yeah.

00:59:39.210 --> 00:59:42.400
Q I'd be hurting right now.
I don't know. I'd probably -- I might approach

00:59:42.400 --> 00:59:43.400
you.

00:59:43.400 --> 00:59:44.400
&gt;&gt; [voices]

00:59:44.400 --> 00:59:49.809
Chris McDougall: Yeah, you'd design something
else and try and capitalize on it, right?

00:59:49.809 --> 00:59:53.900
What they've essentially done is, they've
gone turtle and gone silent.

00:59:53.900 --> 00:59:58.309
And I think it's really scandalous.
And I keep waiting also too for, you know,

00:59:58.309 --> 01:00:01.109
"C'mon, journalistic watchdogs. Wake the fuck
up."

01:00:01.109 --> 01:00:04.200
And, "You guys keep repeating the same shit
over and over again."

01:00:04.200 --> 01:00:11.589
I mean -- not to be too profane and antagonistic.
I'm half-Sicilian, I can't help it, but -- yesterday,

01:00:11.589 --> 01:00:16.499
there's an article in the New York Times,
"Is running barefoot good for you?"

01:00:16.499 --> 01:00:19.529
I thought, "Wait, why isn't this story, 'Is
running in shoes good for you?'"

01:00:19.529 --> 01:00:22.119
Where is the scientific evidence that these
things do anything?

01:00:22.119 --> 01:00:26.779
There's never, ever been an experiment or
a study which indicates that running shoes

01:00:26.779 --> 01:00:30.952
do anything to prevent injuries.
And yet, the default position is somehow,

01:00:30.952 --> 01:00:34.729
"These are good, and bare feet are bad."
So, what are the major shoe manufacturers

01:00:34.729 --> 01:00:36.239
doing?
They're basically keeping their mouth shut.

01:00:36.239 --> 01:00:39.049
They've gotten nothing.
There's no science on their side.

01:00:39.049 --> 01:00:42.690
So essentially, they're going to keep quiet,
wait for this to blow over, and just hope

01:00:42.690 --> 01:00:47.200
that people just keep sleepwalking, you know?
Again, I'm not really faulting the shoe companies,

01:00:47.200 --> 01:00:50.880
you know?
They want to sell garbage, they can sell garbage.

01:00:50.880 --> 01:00:55.549
It's up to people, who are supposed to be
more discriminating, to examine this stuff

01:00:55.549 --> 01:00:58.489
and broadcast it.
I mean, I read you these quotes from the editor

01:00:58.489 --> 01:01:01.809
of Runners World, you know?
Why isn't this dude owning this thing?

01:01:01.809 --> 01:01:07.609
Well, you know, you might suggest that, "because
his magazine sells a lot of running shoes."

01:01:07.609 --> 01:01:09.529
So their response today has been absolute
silence.

01:01:09.529 --> 01:01:12.519
I've not seen a single quote from anybody
about anything responding to this thing yet.

01:01:12.519 --> 01:01:13.519
Q Interesting. Thank you.

01:01:13.519 --> 01:01:16.059
Chris McDougall: Yeah, thanks a lot.

01:01:16.059 --> 01:01:18.369
Q [inaudible]

01:01:18.369 --> 01:01:22.950
Chris McDougall: No. I mean, there's still
shoes.

01:01:22.950 --> 01:01:27.589
You know, barefoot is barefoot, and there's
been sort of a confusion about terminology.

01:01:27.589 --> 01:01:31.320
No one's really quite sure.
I saw someone refer to it as 'natural running'

01:01:31.320 --> 01:01:33.549
the other day.
I thought, "That's probably the best term

01:01:33.549 --> 01:01:36.930
I've heard."
Bill Rogers, you know, the great American

01:01:36.930 --> 01:01:41.819
marathoner -- guy actually owns running shoe
stores -- he said, you know, "The shoe that

01:01:41.819 --> 01:01:45.849
allows your foot to act as if it's barefoot,
that's the shoe you want."

01:01:45.849 --> 01:01:51.359
And that's essentially what it's all about.
Protection is always better than no protection,

01:01:51.359 --> 01:01:55.180
but not to the point where the protection
starts to take over and the give orders.

01:01:55.180 --> 01:01:58.339
Kind of like, you know, the Terminator, the
cyborgs have become self-aware?

01:01:58.339 --> 01:02:02.059
You don't want the shoes to become self-aware.
You want your foot to give the orders, and

01:02:02.059 --> 01:02:04.329
not the shoe.
So, I mean, this one's good.

01:02:04.329 --> 01:02:07.380
I mean, there are plenty of shoes out there.
What I like about this one is the fact that,

01:02:07.380 --> 01:02:09.799
everywhere your foot goes, this thing goes
too.

01:02:09.799 --> 01:02:14.279
It's never sort of left behind.
That's it?

01:02:14.279 --> 01:02:15.279
Cool. Hey guys, thank you.
Thanks.

